04892nam a22005775i 9780822382034DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t19961996ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223820347 a10.1515/97808223820342doi  a(DE-B1597)553708  a(OCoLC)1226680255  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aDS821.5.C5bH68 1996 7aHIS0080002bisacsh04a303.48/251052090342221 aHowland, Douglas, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBorders of Chinese Civilization :bGeography and History at Empire's End /cDouglas Howland; Harry Harootunian, Rey Chow, Masao Miyoshi. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[1996] 4cÂ©1996  a1 online resource (352 p.) :b4 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAsia-Pacific: Culture, Politics, and Society00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tNote -- tIntroduction -- tI Encountering Japan -- t1. Civilization from the Center: The Geomoral Context of Tributary Expectations -- t2 Civilization as Universal Practice The Context of Writing and Poetry -- tII Representing Japan -- tPrologue: Geographical Knowledge and Forms of Representation -- t3. Journeys to the East: The Geography of Historical Sites and Self in the Travelogue -- t4 The Historiographical Use of Poetry -- t5 The Utility of Objectification in the Geographic Treatise -- tIII Representing Japan's Westernization -- t6 Negotiating Civilization and Westernization -- tAfterword -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tGlossary -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aD. R. Howland explores China's representations of Japan in the changing world of the late nineteenth century and, in so doing, examines the cultural and social borders between the two neighbors. Looking at Chinese accounts of Japan written during the 1870s and 1880s, he undertakes an unprecedented analysis of the main genres the Chinese used to portray Japan-the travel diary, poetry, and the geographical treatise. In his discussion of the practice of "brushtalk," in which Chinese scholars communicated with the Japanese by exchanging ideographs, Howland further shows how the Chinese viewed the communication of their language and its dominant modes-history and poetry-as the textual and cultural basis of a shared civilization between the two societies.With Japan's decision in the 1870s to modernize and westernize, China's relationship with Japan underwent a crucial change-one that resulted in its decisive separation from Chinese civilization and, according to Howland, a destabilization of China's worldview. His examination of the ways in which Chinese perceptions of Japan altered in the 1880s reveals the crucial choice faced by the Chinese of whether to interact with Japan as "kin," based on geographical proximity and the existence of common cultural threads, or as a "barbarian," an alien force molded by European influence.By probing China's poetic and expository modes of portraying Japan, Borders of Chinese Civilization exposes the changing world of the nineteenth century and China's comprehension of it. This broadly appealing work will engage scholars in the fields of Asian studies, Chinese literature, history, and geography, as well as those interested in theoretical reflections on travel or modernism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aChinesezJapanxEthnic identity. 7aHISTORY / Asia / China.2bisacsh1 aChow, Rey, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHarootunian, Harry, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMiyoshi, Masao, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999z978311071360240uhttps://d